-- Hong Kong shares close up on strong U.S. data, China rally
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Mon Dec 08, 2014 03:16AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 8 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares rose on Monday, heartened by strong U.S. employment data and as China shares continued to outperform on the back of a blistering rally in mainland markets.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> crossed 3,000 points for the first time since 2011 on Monday as weak trade data spurred expectations that Beijing will roll out further stimulus measures to shore up the cooling economy. The Hang Seng index <.HSI> rose 0.2 percent, to 24,047.67 points, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> gained 2.4 percent, to 11,873.41 points.Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were CCT Land Holdings <0261.HK>, down 5.6 percent at HK$0.02, Bank Of China <3988.HK>, up 4.6 percent at HK$4.32 and CCB <0939.HK>, up 3.9 percent at HK$6.41. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 0.52 billion yuan of the 10.5 billion yuan daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>. Total trading volume of companies included in the HSI index was 3.8 billion shares.